segments.text: First, Mr. Leeper, tell us something about your early life, including the names of your parents, the dates of their birth and death, the places of their birth, the place and date of your birth, and the schools you attended before going to Texas A&M.
Well, like I say, my father was born in Tennessee.
He was born in 1846.
And my mother was born down here in Parker County.
You know where Weatherford is?
She was born in Weatherford.
See, my father, he died in 1924.
He was 79, right at 79.
And my mother died in 1922, and she was around 52 when she died.
He was quite a bit older than she was.
So that's what you want to know.
Yeah, now, were they married in Weatherford?
So his family moved to Texas from Tennessee sometime after he was born.
No, no.
He was, like I say, he was born in Tennessee and in military school and ran off from military school and joined the Confederate Army, old Nathan Forrest Cavalry.
You've heard of Forrest Raiders, I guess.
Yeah.
He was in Nathan Forrest Cavalry.
He was about 16.

and he went through the Civil War and then he afterwards went to St. Louis and things got pretty rough there you know after that reconstruction so he went to St. Louis and he was in the grain business in St. Louis and for some reason he left there and then he come out to Texas he had a charge of Singer Showing Machine Company for that is he was a
an agent for the Singer Sewing Machine Company for four or five years.
He quit that and come over to Weatherford and put in a business.
I think he came to Weatherford in 1878.
What kind of business was that?
Well, he sold sewing machines and organs and sugar mills and old bicycles.

uh all kinds of musical instruments and like that see and then he had a farm too had afterwards as i grew up he had a couple of farms out in the country he used to rent them and uh that was uh that was a kind of he just stayed with it you know like all these old fellas did till he went broke that's the way they used to do it and then the good road came in from fort worth and that uh
killed a small town.
Weatherford at one time was one of the biggest jobbing centers in even bigger than Fort Worth at one time.
They used to do business all out here in the west as far as Abilene and Pecos, even Pecos.
They had four big jobbing houses, wholesale grocers there in Weatherford at one time.
Did they ship out by rail?
Shipped by rail.
Always.
There's no other way, you see.
And then you were born in Weatherford?
I was born in Weatherford.
And when was that?
I was born in 1899, October the 7th.
I'm nearly 75 now.
You went through all the school that they had in Weatherford then?
Yeah, I went to high school there, Weatherford High School.
And then I went to A&M from there.
How did you happen to choose A&M?
Well, I'll tell you.
My dad used to have...
had standard bred horses.
He raised standard bred horses.
That's trotting horses, see.
So he used to race them over at the Dallas Fair.
They had trotting races over there.
So I was a little old kid, you know.
I guess about 12 years old, something like that.
So he was German, and he believed in Disneyland, you know.
He was great for it.

when he told me to do anything I didn't I might ask questions but I asked questions after I did it see that's the way they raised them then and when I if I was in a room and somebody come in I popped up out of that chair and I stood there and I had my chair and all that and when my mother went calling why
I sat over in the corner in the chair, and I didn't make a peep until somebody spoke to me.
See, that's the way the kids were brought up, that is, most of them.
And so anyway, we were over there one time at this racetrack, and A&M Cadet Corps happened to be there.
They were the ferry, you know, and they were one of the attractions.
So they put on a drill out there, and they
in the center of the racetrack, you know.
And it impressed him, and he says, boy, he says, that's a pretty good school.
He says, I want you to go there.
So that's his decision, see.
And of course, it was my decision, too.
I liked it.
And we had a great school in 23.
And it'll never be repeated.
So the military aspect was...
He was in military school.
His parents were pretty well off, you know, in Tennessee.
They sent him to military school, sent all the boys to military school.
So that appealed to both of you then?
Well, it appealed to me, yeah.
I liked it.
I'd heard him talk about the Civil War, you know.
He was a great guy.
He never believed in pampering anybody.
The tougher anything was...
He expected you to do it.
That was all.
He lived hard.
He didn't give a damn.
He lived hard.
He didn't believe in pampering anybody.
In other words, he was out there and the horse pitched you off and he'd tell you to get up and get back on it.
That's the way it is.
What were your first reactions to the school when you got there?
Well, I just fell in with the boys, you know.
It's far different from what it is now.
There's a lot of paddles around.
I presume you arrived by train?
Oh, sure.
We got there at 4 o'clock in the afternoon on what they used to call the Jenny.
The 4 o'clock Jenny.
Houston, what is that?
Houston and Texas Central, I believe.
That's right.
Anyway, we called it the Jenny.
One of them come in at 3 o'clock, and another one come in at 4 o'clock, and another one come in about 4 o'clock in the morning, 3, 4 o'clock in the morning.
Was there anybody there to meet you?
Oh, hell no.
No?
Oh, we didn't.
That stuff, that stuff's old.
That's new-fashioned stuff.
Well, I was wondering, some of the people who were there about your time said they were upperclassmen there to meet you.
and to escort you back to campus or to recruit you to live in a particular dormitory or something.
Is somebody that was there when I was?
Yeah.
Huh?
Yeah.
Were there any students to meet the train, upperclassmen students?
Well, I was a little early, I guess.
And so...
I got off the train there at four o'clock in the afternoon, I think it was somewhere around there.
I remember there were some engineers, these summer engineers, you know, they were out surveying.
I was early.
I was earlier than ordinarily I would be if I had followed schedule, but I went down there a little early.

We went up that old main drag, you know, down to the, up to the administration building and those engineers were out there and I remember they had one, two, three, four, one, two, three, four of these.
So then there's some
The farther I got, I met some boys with paddles, and they were slapping those paddles on their legs, you know.
And so we got on up to the dormitory.
Hell, we didn't know where.
I had a couple of boys from my hometown with me.
So we didn't know what to do, and so we spent the first night in Goodwin Hall, old Goodwin Hall.
Where do you weigh them up?
And you mentioned you spent the first night in Goodwin Hall.
I was in Goodwin Hall.
That's where I spent the first night.
And I remember I had all my bedding and everything packed up in my trunk.
And the trunk was on the road, see?
And so I didn't have anything but a suitcase.
And so we spent the first night in Goodwin Hall and didn't have any sheets and anything.
So we just slept in our clothes.
So the next day, we registered.
And finally, I picked a boy from Weatherford as my roommate, a boy named Byron.
We called him Goat Byron, old Goat Byron.
He's still down there in Weatherford.
Retired from the Dallas Power and Light.
Engineer, mechanical engineer.
So we spent the first night there in Weatherford.
And you remember hearing them talk about old Casey?
Casey's confectioner, yeah.
Casey's confectioner.
Well, we got up the next morning and went in there and ate breakfast.
And old Casey, he had that chew of the back of his mouth, you know.
And he had one eye, you know, Casey did.
Some defect in his eye here.
But he was a character, old Casey was.
Well, then we got in Milner Hall.
put up in Milner Hall, and as I say, we were the first, long first to get there, and we had a thick of a room, see.
So we run over and looked at the things over, and we picked out a nice room on the second floor of Milner Hall, corner room, see.
So we were just fixed up pretty good.
So about the second night we were there, about 3 o'clock in the morning, we heard the biggest tail raising you ever heard coming up those steel stairs.
And somebody coming running in there.
You know, it was summertime.
We never thought anything about closing the door.
And somebody coming running in there.
And he says, here's a couple of fish in here, in our room.
And you remember, you've heard about old Cop Forsyth?
Yeah.
Well, Cop's brother made that big donation, you know, to the college, $300,000.
Yeah.
And that was old Cop's brother, kid brother.
Yeah.
And he was a sophomore that year.
So he rousted us out of there.
You talk about getting met at the station, that's...
He rousted us out of there pretty quick.
So he told us out of their room.
Of course, it's against the rules then, you know, for any freshman to get in the corner room.
That was a bad breach of etiquette.
A freshman had to be in one of these middle rooms.
So old cop, he run us out of that room about 3 o'clock, about when the genie come in, the 3 o'clock genie, run us out of that room.
He and old Stovall, there's a fellow named J.T.
Stovall,
Well, you ever heard of him or not, old J.T.?
I don't think so.
He's dead now.
So is Cop, I think.
Now, Cop's still alive.
The young Cop, little Cop.
Well, the one I know is Cop Forsyth, class of 13 or something like that.
Well, that's his brother.
That's his brother.
And that was the original Cop, see?
I might be talking out of school now, but I don't want to...

get mixed up maybe in something i don't know about but this they call little cop oh he was a young he was he was a sophomore and he'd had an older brother there named a cop and i don't know whether it's this one that donated to school or not but the tradition went the story went that when the a m defeated texas in uh
I believe it was 1912, 1911, sometime back there.
That wouldn't be the exact date.
They used to have a big old steer, you know, a longhorn steer for a mascot.
So they got this longhorn steer and branded him 18-6.
What was the score?
I forget.
I believe they branded him 13-0.
Yeah, that's it.
You're right.
So...
They were raising hell there in town, you know, that night and so some of these old policemen used to wear these long coats and helmets and so forth.
So the story went that the policemen started to arrest some of these boys and so they just
threw him down, stripped his clothes off, stripped his uniform off, and the old cop dressed up, and he acted as a policeman, so that's where he got the name of cop.
Oh, I see.
That was a tradition when I was there, see.
And so his little brother, his younger brother was Little Cop.
Little Cop.
See, when that fellow went to school there, and his name was Cop, then the next, the next, not generation, but the next kin that come there, he automatically became Little Cop, see.
Like there's a Big Hig and a Little Hig.
Old Little Hig, he was there when I was there, you know, and he was a big athlete and a big halfback there.
And Big Hig was about three, four years before him.
So anyway, we got run out of that room, and then we found us a room down the hall a little ways, and that's where we put up for the rest of the time.
So that's the kind of, and so we became then, I was the top fish,
I was old Stovall's fish, and this other boy was Byron.
He was old Cop's fish.
So we had to go down every morning, clean out the room for him, sweep it up.
And he'd tell us, I don't want any ram fish.
Get that room clean.
Well, that was our job.
We had to clean up the room, wash the wash basin, and all like that every morning after breakfast before class.
And that's the way to run things.
Did you have to clean the rifle, too?
clean the rifles.
Every Saturday morning for inspection, we had to clean the rifles.
And they had to stay in inspection every Saturday.
And if it was, sometimes it was room inspection, something come up, maybe they didn't want to have them.
So they had room inspection.
We had to be, we were, we did guard duty.
We'd run at walk post.
And
all that sort of thing, drilled three times a week.
And that is Tuesday we drilled, and Thursday we drilled, and then Saturday we either had an inspection or had a review on the, an inspection on the parade grounds, a review.
So it was a mighty fine school.
Did you stay in Milner Hall the whole time you were there?
No.
I was in Milner Hall my freshman year, and then my roommate got assigned to my roommate and I got assigned to E Company, and E Company was up in Bazell.
So I roomed in Bazell the rest of the time.
Those two were both fairly new, Don and Fuente.
Well, they just finished Brazell.
And when I went there as a freshman, they just finished the previous year.
And that was the brand newest thing on the campus was Brazell Hall.
That was a nice hall.
So you had convenient showers and bathrooms and all that sort of stuff in those.
Well, it's a.
You had them on each floor anyway.
Yeah, we had them on.
We did the same thing in Milton.
We had latrines, we called it, on each floor.
How was the life in those dormitories?
Was it pretty hectic or pretty well controlled or how would you describe it?
It's nothing like it is now.
Oh, hell no.
We had discipline, you know.
We had call to quarters every night.
I think, as well as I recollect, it was either 7 or 7.15 was call to quarters.
Well, 7 was call to quarters and then we
had room inspection.
We had to be in a room by 7.15.
And then we had a fellow sent in a walking post on each floor.
And if you wanted to go out for anything, you had to holler for him and ask his permission to go with the latrine or something like that, or toilet.
And you couldn't go out to the library or stuff like that unless you got permission.
You had to have permission to go out.
Freshmen
He could get one pass a month to Brian.
A sophomore could get one pass a week.
And a junior could go every Saturday when he wanted to.
And a senior could go anytime he wanted to.
Go anywhere.
And the seniors run the school.
He could go anywhere he had enough money to go.
Well, he couldn't just take off.
In other words, if he wanted to run down to Navasota,
Why, in my senior year down there, why, my company captain and his 12 more seniors went down to Navasota, got in one of those whorehouses down there and got drunk.
And they found it out, and they canned every one of them.
They wouldn't have done that now, would they?
I doubt it.
Too soft-hearted.
Every one of them got canned right just a few days before Christmas.
They were about half a year from graduating.
Half a year from graduating.
Did they allow any of them to come back, or did they can them permanently?
No, sir.
They kind of canned them for all the time to come.
None of them ever came back at all.
Had I ever heard of them.
I remember Bob Easton was my company commander.
Did that cause any kind of disturbance among the rest of the students?
No, no.
There's three things you mustn't do.
You mustn't gamble.
You mustn't get drunk.
You mustn't cheat.
You mustn't steal.
And those are three things.
That is, those are the things that you must not do.
That is, under the penalty of being expelled.
They caught you gambling, playing poker.
They raided the poker room.
Every fellow...
in that room got canned, whether he was playing poker or not.
Just watch it.
He got canned.
And if you got drunk, they found it out, you got the tag.
Well, they don't do that today for sure because I think most of them had beer in their rooms.
That's right.
Well, I say, we had a school.
We had a school.
Now, don't forget it, boys.
2,300 cadets.
And we had discipline.
We walked posts.
And we did drill.
We went to summer camp.
And everybody had to take military training.
Did upperclassmen as well as freshmen walk posts?
Oh, no, no.
Just the freshmen walked the posts?
No, just the freshmen.
And that was only inside the dormitories, wasn't it?
Yeah, inside.
In other words, you're supposed to keep these kids in their room.
Yeah.
They couldn't leave their room unless they got permission from you.
We had the sergeant of the guard and all that kind of stuff, you know.
Officer of the day.
Officer of the day, yeah, we had an officer of the day every day.
Was it the officer of the day who inspected the rooms?
Or was it the company commander?
No, the room inspection was, we had an old sergeant down there, he called him Sergeant Smart.
And he had some assistance.
We had some of these old-time army sergeants down there, but...
As a rule, old Sergeant Smart went around every morning and inspected the room, see.
He found a dirty wash basin, a bed unmade, or anything, dust, dirt on the floor, or anything.
In other words, the room wasn't tidy.
You got a red slip in the mailbox.
Mm-hmm.
If you was a freshman and you was cleaning that upperclassman's room, you got the paddle.
The upperclassman got the ram, but you got the paddle.
You got the paddle.
How did they work it, say, if there were two of you in the room and the wash basin was dirty, you both got a ram?
Both of us got around.
But if just one bed was messed up, why, who's every bed it was got around?
It didn't make any difference whose bed it was.
That room got around.
That room got around.
Did they read that list at the mess hall at night?
No.
No, you just got a red flip, and that gave you so many demerits.
Well, if I remember right, 125 demerits in one semester, they sent you home.
If you missed retreat, you missed formation, any kind of a formation, well, you got a ram.
You got a ram clip.
Well, if you got the, I think it was 125.
I've still got my old blue buck in there.
How could you reduce the number you had?
Couldn't reduce them.
Hell, that was permanent.
Well, there was a point at one time where you could work on the grounds or something for the school and reduce the range.
Well, I know that's where the liberality first came.
Or you could march in the bullring and reduce them.
Well, they didn't have anything like that then.
There are different ways you got a demerit.
If you missed flash, you cut flash, you got a demerit.
If you missed formation, you got a demerit.
If your room was untidy, you got a demerit.
If your gun was dirty at inspection, you got a demerit.
I don't know what the number was, but a certain number for each fence.
If you got the magic number, you were out.
That's right.
You went home.
You couldn't come back until the next semester.
You had to get out on your knees and say a prayer before they let you in there.
What was the food like in the mess hall?
Good.
It was all right.
Old freezer stuff, we called it.
It was all right.
Was it kind of monotonous at times?
Well, I wouldn't say that.
They fed us good.
We had chili, and we had bull necks, and we had plenty of bread, and we had cereal.
It was all right.
Just plain, wholesome food, you see.
It was all right.
We had a table style, and they had Mexican waiters bring us the food.
We sat 12 men at the table.
And the upperclassman, he always had the end chair at the head of the table.
They had an upperclassman at the head of the table.
and had one at their foot.
And when we went in, well, we stood at attention until all the corps was in.
And then the colonel gave the command, take seats.
We took seats.

But before you took seats, why then you wanted to see that each upperclassman, maybe sometimes there was a sophomore, maybe a junior sergeant at the head of the table, maybe a sergeant at the foot, maybe a sophomore seat.
You wanted to be pretty sure that those glasses were all filled with water or iced tea or whatever they wanted before you sat down.
And they were well served and well taken care of.
And then when everybody was helped, the sophomores or the upperclassmen helped themselves, well, then we dove in and helped ourselves.
Those things are good for a boy.
I know you marched to every meal in formation.
Marched to every meal, yes, sir.
Did you enter the dining hall in the same order all the time?
In other words, the same company go in first all the time?
That's right.
We just started in at the head down there.
Whichever one was closest to the speech hall on the military walk.
They lined up in front of you.
You know how that main drag was.
I mean, the military walk.
You know how that was arranged there.
Dormitories on each side, so we fell out naturally to fall out for formation, retreat, and stuff like that.
fell out that way.
Adjacent to the holes, we marched in every day.
Everything was run in the military matters.
You know that, you probably know this, that A&M furnished more officers for World War I than the two in the United States.
Yeah, and I'm not sure, I believe the same is true for two, World War II.
I mean World War II, that's what I mean, not World War I, now I don't know, but World War II.
I believe it was both of them.
We mentioned a few things earlier that the upper classmen could do that the freshmen couldn't, like they could go to town more often and
and they had freshmen to do things for them, and they got served first in the dining hall and that sort of stuff.
Were there any other privileges that the upperclassmen had?
Well, they had all the privileges that were graded by, as I told you, it started from the sophomore.
Of course, he had the first bottom privilege, and then it went on up to the senior.
And he had the senior.
I guess you suppose heI would say he had all the privileges.
What did you do for entertainment and recreation?
Oh, we didn't suffer that.
Played poker and blackjack and behind the locked doors and
And we had a theater every Saturday night, a picture show down there.
We went to that, and then we had dances.
Was that a picture show in the old air dome?
Well, there's an old wooden shack they had there.
I don't know what they called it.
I think it was the air dome.
Yeah, it was built out of wood.
Was that over there across from the YMCA?
Yeah, that's back right in front of the YMCA.
Yeah, I believe that was the old air dome.
Yeah, that's what they called it, I guess, the air dome.
It wasn't a very big building.
We had these movies over there.
And we had lots of fun, you know.
We went berry hunting, and we went out to the fish tank.
You know where the fish tank is?
No.
No?
A bunch of sportsmen started that way back, and that's where they used to take the fish out there and dump them and throw them in that fish tank, and that's where it got its name, the fish tank.
Where was it, say, from the administration building, if you went across the railroad tracks down that direction?
The fish tank?
Yeah.
Yeah, it was out there on the other side of the way, out in the country there.
That was about, I'd say, about four miles, as far as I recollect, about four miles from Bryant.
There was no tank out there, just a lake.
They called it a lake.
I think a bunch of sportsmen started it, and maybe it was abandoned, I don't know.
But we used to go swimming out there, and...
There's a lot of blackberries out in that part of the woods.
We used to go out there and just rove around.
We had a lot of wholesome, we had a more wholesome form of living than these people have now, you know.
I guess it's that way all over the country.
